PAGA Tutorial

Abstract¶

 PAGA (Partition-based Graph Abstraction) is a powerful tool available in Scanpy designed for analyzing single-cell RNA sequencing data. It enables the exploration of cellular relationships, trajectory inference, and understanding of cell state transitions by modeling single-cell data as a graph. For more information, please visit the Scanpy Website.

2-2. Denoising the Graph in Diffusion map¶

This step is not necessary but helps to denoise the graph by computing distances within a few diffusion components. We use a few of the first spectral components to denoise the data. It is similar to PCA-based denoising.

In [6]:
sc.tl.diffmap(adata)
sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_neighbors=10, use_rep='X_diffmap')

3. Constructing the pseudotime and PAGA¶

Return to Index

 After calculating PAGA, we proceed to calculate pseudotime. The goal of this tutorial is to create the Tenet input, and pseudotime is part of this. Therefore, running PAGA is optional. For detailed information about PAGA, please refer to the LINK.


___

3-1. PAGA¶

PAGA (Partition-based Graph Abstraction) represents cell-to-cell relationships as a graph, highlighting connections and interactions between different cell types. Interpreting the PAGA graph provides insights into cell relationships and system-level properties within the dataset.

The data we are using may not result in a beautifully drawn PAGA graph. Therefore, we have not plotted the graph. However, if you wish to visualize the graph, please erase the following code.

  • plot = False
In [8]:
sc.tl.paga(adata, groups='leiden')
sc.pl.paga(adata, color=['leiden'], plot = False)

3-2. Pseudotime¶

Predict the Differentiation process from the root region using trajectory calculations. In our data, we arbitrarily set initiating from CD4 T cells. If you want another initiating cell, change it.

In [15]:
adata.uns['iroot'] = np.flatnonzero(adata.obs['leiden']  == 'CD4 T')[0]
In [16]:
sc.tl.dpt(adata)
sc.pl.draw_graph(adata, color=['leiden', 'dpt_pseudotime'], legend_loc='on data')

    'dpt_pseudotime', the pseudotime (adata.obs) (0:00:00)

sc.pl.umap(adata,color='dpt_pseudotime')

4. Prepare Tenet Input¶

Return to Index

 As the final step, we create the Tenet Input. To create the Tenet Input, Three files are required.

  • Raw Count matrix
  • Cell-Gene matrix
  • Pseudotime

 Here, we use the Raw count matrix, which was prepared separately during the Scanpy process. Regarding the Cell-Gene matrix, there is one assumption: we will use all cells. Therefore, we need select the genes we want to use. And pseudotime is already calculated in previous code.

Create Tenet Input.

In [19]:
def TENET_input_make(adata, directory='/home/Users/write'):
    # Set 'cell_select' column to '1' for all observations
    adata.obs['cell_select'] = '1'

    # Extract the required columns
    input_data = adata.obs[['dpt_pseudotime', 'cell_select']]

    # Save pseudotime to a CSV file
    input_data['dpt_pseudotime'].to_csv(f'{directory}/pseudotime.csv', index=False, header=False)

    # Save cell_select to a CSV file
    input_data['cell_select'].to_csv(f'{directory}/cell_select.csv', index=False, header=False)
In [20]:
TENET_input_make(adata)
